  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>A Technical Proposal is Not a Technical Document</h3>
    <p>It’s natural for technical professionals to approach proposals like technical reports, full of detail and precision. But a proposal is something else entirely: it’s a persuasive tool. Its job is to help a client say “yes” with confidence. That means going beyond technical accuracy to show a clear understanding of the project’s goals, stakeholders, and broader context. Strong proposals convey not just what you can build, but how you’ll respond to change, stay on schedule, and manage the most unpredictable element of any project—people.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>A Discipline All Its Own</h3>
    <p>Proposals deserve the same level of structure and care as any project. In fact, every proposal *is* a project—and it benefits from a dedicated manager. Not all firms have full-time proposal staff, but all can benefit from adopting smart practices and clearly defined roles. The proposal manager brings clarity, coordination, and momentum to what is often a fast-moving, high-stakes effort. Twennie’s library helps fill a critical gap by offering tools and strategies designed specifically for proposal work in technical environments.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>The Non-Technical Professional in a Technical World</h3>
    <p>Proposal managers often come from non-technical backgrounds, but they bring essential skills to the table: project coordination, persuasive writing, business acumen, and the ability to bring teams together. Their success depends on influence, not authority. They need to organize, communicate, and lead across disciplines, often without formal control. Twennie is committed to supporting these professionals with tailored resources that help them thrive in technical settings—and help technical teams make the most of their contributions.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Managing a Portfolio of Proposals</h3>
    <p>Winning work through proposals is never guaranteed, but it shouldn’t feel like a guessing game. Many organizations submit multiple proposals before securing a win, which reflects not just tough competition, but gaps in process and learning. Writing proposals is one of the most expensive business development activities, so it pays to look closely at what works, what doesn’t, and why. Twennie helps firms move beyond trial and error by offering strategies to track, evaluate, and refine their approach to competitive pursuits.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Defining Value Through the Client’s Eyes</h3>
    <p>Great proposals start with a simple but powerful question: *What does the client value?* That doesn’t just mean meeting the minimum requirements in the RFP. It means thinking beyond the checklist. Most clients begin with baseline expectations, but their decision-making happens above that line. What makes them excited? What builds trust? What makes your proposal feel different from the others? Twennie encourages a shift in perspective—from simply qualifying for the work to showing why your approach delivers something uniquely valuable.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>The Tailored Proposal</h3>
    <p>No two clients are the same and no two proposals should be either. While it may be tempting to reuse language or templates, true differentiation comes from understanding each client’s priorities and crafting a response that speaks directly to them. If a client has spent months planning their project, they deserve a proposal that reflects that effort. Twennie helps professionals develop the insight and creativity needed to shape proposals that resonate, build trust, and stand out from the crowd.</p>
